lead_paragraph: A small group of paleontologists recently discovered 10 species of ancient mammals previously unknown to science. But they had an enormous number of helpers at their dig site: thousands of tiny ants.

headline.main: They Uncover New Fossils, but They Also Bite
headline.print_headline: They Uncover Fossils, But They Also Bite

abstract: Fossils found in southwestern China give a hint to the development of the panda's sixth digit — a rudimentary, thumblike bone extension.
snippet: Fossils found in southwestern China give a hint to the development of the panda's sixth digit — a rudimentary, thumblike bone extension.
lead_paragraph: Giant pandas are dietary enigmas. Despite being part of the meat-eating order Carnivora, pandas typically practice a plant-based diet, eschewing salmon and seal meat at the bear family barbecue for shoots of bamboo. And because they lack multichambered stomachs to extract nutrients from the tough plant material, the pudgy bears eat around 30 pounds of bamboo each day to sustain themselves.

headline.main: Who's Got Two Pseudothumbs and Loves to Eat Bamboo? This Bear.
headline.print_headline: A Digital Display: Two More Pseudothumbs Than Your Average Bear

abstract: A new study found that primeval rodents, which were estimated to be the size of bison, were closer to modern-day ponies.
snippet: A new study found that primeval rodents, which were estimated to be the size of bison, were closer to modern-day ponies.
lead_paragraph: Modern rodents range in size from pygmy mice weighing less than an ounce to stocky capybaras pushing 175 pounds. But even the largest capybara is a pipsqueak compared with some prehistoric rodents that resembled a cross between a supersized capybara and a hairy hippopotamus. Paleontologists estimate that one, Phoberomys pattersoni, may have weighed as much as 1,300 pounds. Another, Josephoartigasia monesi, was believed to be around 2,000 pounds, as big as a bison.

headline.main: Earth's Largest Rodents Were Smaller Than We Once Thought
headline.print_headline: Rodents Once the Size of Bison? Findings Call That a Stretch.

abstract: By studying chemical signatures in fossilized tusks, researchers have pieced together one of the elephant-like animal's movements and maladies.
snippet: By studying chemical signatures in fossilized tusks, researchers have pieced together one of the elephant-like animal's movements and maladies.
lead_paragraph: Over 13,000 years ago, an American mastodon roamed what is today the American Midwest. Year after year, he returned to an area in northeast Indiana — believed to be a mating ground. It was there that he died in battle.

headline.main: Fred the Mastodon's Tusks Reveal a Life of Fighting and Roaming
headline.print_headline: Hoosier Heavyweight: Letting Tusks Tell the Tale  Of a Mastodon Named Fred

abstract: The origin of the domestic fowl is more recent than previously thought, but it may have taken them thousands of years to become food.
snippet: The origin of the domestic fowl is more recent than previously thought, but it may have taken them thousands of years to become food.
lead_paragraph: The real chicken mystery has nothing to do with whether the egg came first. Scientists would like to know when, where and how a bird of the jungle came together with human farmers to begin down the path that eventually led to the Popeyes chicken sandwich.

headline.main: Before Chickens Were Nuggets, They Were Revered
headline.print_headline: Before Joining Menus, Chickens Were Revered

abstract: Evolutionary theories said giraffes developed their height to get to better eats, but ancestors may have gained the advantage through head-butting battles.
snippet: Evolutionary theories said giraffes developed their height to get to better eats, but ancestors may have gained the advantage through head-butting battles.
lead_paragraph: Since the days of Charles Darwin, the long necks of giraffes have been a textbook example of evolution. The theory goes that as giraffe ancestors competed for food, those with longer necks were able to reach higher leaves, getting a leg — or neck — up over shorter animals.

headline.main: Giraffes May Be Long-Necked for Fights, Not Just Food
headline.print_headline: Lovestruck: With Ancient Giraffes, Hardheads Had Edge

abstract: The largest shark that ever lived may have vanished in part because the comparatively smaller great white had a taste for the same prey.
snippet: The largest shark that ever lived may have vanished in part because the comparatively smaller great white had a taste for the same prey.
lead_paragraph: Twenty million years ago, a predator with a mouth like a subway door and teeth the size of your palm roamed the seas. The megalodon, the largest shark ever to live on Earth, could grow more than 50 feet long, and it was the scourge of the ocean for millions of years. Then it disappeared. The megalodon was no more.

headline.main: Megalodons vs. Great White Sharks? We Know Which Predator Won.
headline.print_headline: Evolutionary Battleground: Megalodons vs. Great White Sharks?  We Know Which Predator Won.

abstract: Scientists directly measured the metabolic rate of extinct animals, which revealed that some giant dinosaurs became coldblooded.
snippet: Scientists directly measured the metabolic rate of extinct animals, which revealed that some giant dinosaurs became coldblooded.
lead_paragraph: Paleontologists have long wrangled with the question of dinosaur metabolisms — whether they ran hot, like modern birds and mammals do, or resembled the slower metabolisms of modern reptiles. In a surprise, the answer seems to be both.

headline.main: Dinosaurs Started Out Hot, Then Some of Them Turned Cold
headline.print_headline: Paleontological Metabolism: After Dinosaurs' Hot Start, A Long and Chilly Evolution

abstract: A molar discovered in a cave in Laos shows where the enigmatic Denisovans could have interbred with the ancestors of modern humans.
snippet: A molar discovered in a cave in Laos shows where the enigmatic Denisovans could have interbred with the ancestors of modern humans.
lead_paragraph: A tooth found inside of a mountain cave in Laos has solved one of the biggest scientific mysteries of the Denisovans, a branch of ancient humans that disappeared roughly 50,000 years ago.

headline.main: Tooth of an Ancient Girl Fills Gap in Human Family Tree
headline.print_headline: Ancient Tooth Fills Gap in Human Family Tree

abstract: A new study suggests that a widespread species of the ancient feline predators concealed their deadly teeth when they weren't on the attack.
snippet: A new study suggests that a widespread species of the ancient feline predators concealed their deadly teeth when they weren't on the attack.
lead_paragraph: Close your eyes and picture being face-to-face with a saber-toothed cat. Most likely you'll see in your frightened mind's eye the long, curved upper canines — particularly sinister because those dagger-shaped teeth remained in full view, even when the cat closed its mouth.

headline.main: We've Been Drawing These Saber-Tooth Cats All Wrong
headline.print_headline: Drawing the Wrong Conclusion All These Years

abstract: The discovery of clasper limbs in a fossil suggests that some species of the ancient arthropods reproduced much like modern horseshoe crabs.
snippet: The discovery of clasper limbs in a fossil suggests that some species of the ancient arthropods reproduced much like modern horseshoe crabs.
lead_paragraph: The sturdy, calcite-infused exoskeletons of trilobites and their segmented shells are nearly ubiquitous in fossil deposits from the Cambrian Period to the Permian. But this trove of trilobite fossils has revealed frustratingly little when it comes to how the Paleozoic animals reproduced across 250 million years of living on ancient Earth.

headline.main: Before There Were Birds or Bees, This Is How Trilobites Made Babies
headline.print_headline: Paleozoic Passion: Before There Were Birds or Bees, How Trilobites Reproduced

abstract: Researchers described Annakacygna, a family of flightless ancient swans that were filter-feeders.
snippet: Researchers described Annakacygna, a family of flightless ancient swans that were filter-feeders.
lead_paragraph: It's not unusual today to find swans on rivers and lakes, splitting their time between pulling up water plants and punishing the unwise with powerful blows of their bony-elbowed wings.

headline.main: The ‘Ultimate Bird' Once Prowled the Seas of a Young Japan
headline.print_headline: ‘Ultimate Birds': Once Prowling the Seas of Japan, A Family of Flightless Swans

abstract: In a North Dakota deposit far from the Chicxulub crater in Mexico, remains of the rock from space were preserved within amber, a paleontologist says.
snippet: In a North Dakota deposit far from the Chicxulub crater in Mexico, remains of the rock from space were preserved within amber, a paleontologist says.
lead_paragraph: GREENBELT, Md. — Pristine slivers of the impactor that killed the dinosaurs have been discovered, said scientists studying a North Dakota site that is a time capsule of that calamitous day 66 million years ago.

headline.main: Shards of Asteroid That Killed the Dinosaurs May Have Been Found in Fossil Site
headline.print_headline: Shards of Space Rock That Killed Dinosaurs May Have Been Found at Fossil Site

abstract: A team of Italian scientists describe what they believe is a gaping scar from one of these ancient battles on the neck frill of the Triceratops.
snippet: A team of Italian scientists describe what they believe is a gaping scar from one of these ancient battles on the neck frill of the Triceratops.
lead_paragraph: Thanks to dramatic museum displays, many of us can imagine a Triceratops wielding its horns and sprawling neck frill to ward off a hungry Tyrannosaurus rex. But some scientists believe that Triceratopses used their deadly headgear against each other, too. Like dueling elk brandishing their antlers, Triceratopses may have interlocked their horns to woo mates or vanquish rivals.

headline.main: ‘Big John,' a High-Profile Triceratops, Locked Horns With Its Own Kind, Study Suggests
headline.print_headline: Locking Horns: On the Neck of Triceratops, Clear Evidence of an In-House Altercation

abstract: It may have been the smart evolutionary strategy during a chaotic chapter of Earth's history, but it didn't last.
snippet: It may have been the smart evolutionary strategy during a chaotic chapter of Earth's history, but it didn't last.
lead_paragraph: Mammals are the brainiacs of the animal world. The brain of the sperm whale is the largest on Earth, at a hefty 20 pounds, while your three-pound brain is seven times as large as expected for the average human body. Collectively, mammals have the largest ratio of brain to body size among vertebrates, a fact that helps to explain their cognitive ability. Bigger brains are often better at coordinating complex behavior, solving puzzles and responding to environmental change.

headline.main: Dimwitted Mammals Needed Muscle More Than Brains After Dinosaurs Died
headline.print_headline: Muscle-Headed Mammals: After Dinosaurs Disappeared, Lunkheads Loomed Larger

abstract: The bird, which sought prey in a part of China 6 million years ago, had eyes shaped in a way that suggest it was not nocturnal like most owls living today.
snippet: The bird, which sought prey in a part of China 6 million years ago, had eyes shaped in a way that suggest it was not nocturnal like most owls living today.
lead_paragraph: In the silty red soil of Gansu Province in China, a small owl has lain nestled for about 6 million years, since an era known as the Late Miocene. The fossilized bird's talons are outstretched, one of its wings is spread wide and its sharp beak is turned back over its shoulder.

headline.main: Fossil Holds Clues to How Some Owls Evolved Into Daytime Hunters
headline.print_headline: Morning Creatures: Owls in Late Miocene Era  Found It Wise to Rise Early

keywords.value: Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences

abstract: The “king” of the trilobites was snacking on whatever it could eat some 514 million years ago in the Cambrian era, even shelled creatures of its own species.
snippet: The “king” of the trilobites was snacking on whatever it could eat some 514 million years ago in the Cambrian era, even shelled creatures of its own species.
lead_paragraph: Cannibalism is common among the millions of modern arthropod species. A praying mantis consumes her mate after copulation, termites suck blood out of wounded peers, and mosquitoes snack on larvae. But how far back does this gruesome mode of dining go in the history of life feeding on life?

headline.main: Trilobite Fossils Suggest Cannibalism Is More Ancient Than Once Thought
headline.print_headline: Prehistoric Snacks: To Locate the First Cannibals, It Took More Than Just Guts

abstract: Scientists describe a new species of vampyropod from a 328-million-year-old, 10-armed fossil found in Montana.
snippet: Scientists describe a new species of vampyropod from a 328-million-year-old, 10-armed fossil found in Montana.
lead_paragraph: About 328 million years ago, Fergus County, Mont., was no stranger to monsoons. Back then, the region was a marine bay, much like the Bay of Bengal in South Asia. The tropical storms regularly flushed the bay with freshwater and fine sediments, feeding algal blooms and depleting the water of oxygen in certain spots. Anything that died in these spots could have the rare posthumous luck of being preserved, undisturbed.

headline.main: Fossil of Vampire Squid's Oldest Ancestor Is Named for Biden
headline.print_headline: Presidential Fossil: Biden Gets His Own Species. (He's Still Eight Behind Obama.)

abstract: The animals painted in ocher in Colombia may include giant ground sloths and other creatures that vanished from the Americas. But some researchers say the art has a more recent origin.
snippet: The animals painted in ocher in Colombia may include giant ground sloths and other creatures that vanished from the Americas. But some researchers say the art has a more recent origin.
lead_paragraph: At the end of the last ice age, South America was home to strange animals that have since vanished into extinction: giant ground sloths, elephant-like herbivores and an ancient lineage of horses. A new study suggests that we can see these lost creatures in enchanting ocher paintings made by ice age humans on a rocky outcrop in the Colombian Amazon.

headline.main: Does This Amazon Rock Art Depict Extinct Ice Age Mammals?
headline.print_headline: Dazzling Display: In Rock Art From South America, Odd Creatures, Real or Imagined

abstract: The specimen shows that modern tuatara found in New Zealand are little changed from ancestors that lived 190 million years ago.
snippet: The specimen shows that modern tuatara found in New Zealand are little changed from ancestors that lived 190 million years ago.
lead_paragraph: New Zealand's tuatara look like somber iguanas. But these spiny reptiles are not actually lizards. Instead, they are the last remnant of a mysterious and ancient order of reptiles known as the Rhynchocephalians that mostly vanished after their heyday in the Jurassic period.

headline.main: Fossil Reveals Secrets of One of Nature's Most Mysterious Reptiles
headline.print_headline: Steady Specimen: Fossil Helps Release Secrets Of a Most Mysterious Reptile

abstract: The premise, put forth in a new paper, highlights an assortment of tensions in dinosaur paleontology, including how subjective the naming of species can be.
snippet: The premise, put forth in a new paper, highlights an assortment of tensions in dinosaur paleontology, including how subjective the naming of species can be.
lead_paragraph: Tyrannosaurus rex is the most iconic dinosaur. Its skeletons hold pride of place in museums around the world, and sell for millions of dollars at auction — and a bounty of relatively complete specimens have made it the most thoroughly studied dinosaur in the world.

headline.main: They Want to Break T. Rex Into 3 Species. Other Paleontologists Aren't Pleased.
headline.print_headline: T. Rex Might Have Had Close Cousins

abstract: A team of researchers say that rather than occupying their own branch in the history of life on Earth, horseshoe crabs are in the same group as spiders and scorpions.
snippet: A team of researchers say that rather than occupying their own branch in the history of life on Earth, horseshoe crabs are in the same group as spiders and scorpions.
lead_paragraph: Horseshoe crabs are little armored vehicles with bright blue blood. For hundreds of millions of years, they've been trundling along the ocean floor. In all that time, other mighty creatures have come and gone: dinosaurs, mammoths, terror birds, Neanderthals. The humble horseshoe crab has lived on, looking not that different these days from their forebears in the Mesozoic Era.

headline.main: Act of ‘Heresy' Adds Horseshoe Crabs to Arachnid Family Tree
headline.print_headline: Horseshoe Crabs Trapped in a Family Debate

abstract: A new paper suggests Neanderthals and Homo sapiens alternately settled the same shelter more than 50,000 years ago.
snippet: A new paper suggests Neanderthals and Homo sapiens alternately settled the same shelter more than 50,000 years ago.
lead_paragraph: Tens of thousands of years ago, the hottest real estate in Europe was a rock shelter in southern France. Grotte Mandrin had everything a hominin could want. A rocky overhang that offered shelter from the rain. Sweeping views of a valley and the bison and deer roaming below. A prime location in the Rhône Valley, an important natural corridor linking the Mediterranean Basin with northern lands.

headline.main: Neanderthals and Modern Humans Agreed About One Thing: This Cave
headline.print_headline: Hard Evidence: In French Cave, All Signs Point to Prehistoric Timeshare Arrangement

abstract: Opabinia, which swam the seas of Earth's Cambrian era some 500 million years ago, was not just a one hit wonder.
snippet: Opabinia, which swam the seas of Earth's Cambrian era some 500 million years ago, was not just a one hit wonder.
lead_paragraph: Of all the strange creatures unearthed from the Burgess Shale — a cache of remarkable Cambrian fossils deposited in the Canadian Rockies — none has been quite as transfixing as Opabinia. And for good reason — with five compound eyes and a trunk-like nozzle that ended in a claw, Opabinia seems otherworldly, like something imagined in a science fiction novel, rather than a swimmer in Earth's oceans some 500 millions years ago.

headline.main: One of Evolution's Oddest Creatures Finds a Fossilized Family Member
headline.print_headline: Familial Fossils: One of Evolution's Oddballs Finds a Long-Lost Cousin

abstract: A study of fossils from Colombia suggests that a prehistoric shellfish hunted prey with remarkably sharp vision.
snippet: A study of fossils from Colombia suggests that a prehistoric shellfish hunted prey with remarkably sharp vision.
lead_paragraph: Modern, adult crabs are not renowned for their swimming ability or their vision. They scuttle across the floors of silent seas, hardly reliant on small eyes as they scavenge or graze.

headline.main: This Ancient Crab Had Unusually Huge Eyes
headline.print_headline: Visionary Shellfish: In an Ancient Crab, Eyes Worth Taking a Look At

abstract: The find suggests overlooked rocks across the continent may contain more fossilized surprises.
snippet: The find suggests overlooked rocks across the continent may contain more fossilized surprises.
lead_paragraph: Australia's Central Tablelands, hundreds of miles northwest of Sydney, are dominated today by grasses and spindly trees. But scientists recently discovered that some of the area's rusted rocks conceal traces of the lush rainforests that covered the area 15 million years ago during the Miocene Epoch.

headline.main: Fossils of a Prehistoric Rainforest Hide in Australia's Rusted Rocks
headline.print_headline: In Australian Fossils, a Rainforest Beckons
